A Dockerfile is a text file with a set of instructions to build a docker image.
Docker build reads the Dockerfile and produces an image layer by layer.
Eace instruction usually creates a new layer, which can be catched and reuse.


Here is the meaning of each Dockerfile step :-

FROM :- Mandatory first instruction in most Dockerfiles. Sets the base layer of your image.
RUN :- Install Dependencies 
COPY/ADD :- Copies file/directories from build context (local directory) into the image.
WORKDIR :- Sets the working directory for subsequent instructions (RUN, CMD, ENTRY, COPY, ADD)
ENV :- Set environment variables in the image.
EXPOSE :- It informs Docker and humans which ports the container listens on.
CMD :- Default Container Command. Specifies the default container command to run when a container starts.
      Can be overridden by providing a command in docker run.
      Only one CMD is used (last one in Dockerfile if multiple are defined).
